# JavaScript / TypeScript quality

Source: [awesome-cursorrules — javascript-typescript-code-quality-cursorrules-pro](https://github.com/PatrickJS/awesome-cursorrules)

- **Simplicity > cleverness**; fewer lines usually mean less debt.
- **Early returns** to avoid deep nesting; **guard clauses** for invalid input.
- **Descriptive names**; event handlers prefixed with `handle` (e.g. `handleSubmit`).
- Prefer **immutable, functional** patterns when readability stays high.
- **DRY** without premature abstraction — one clear abstraction beats three half-used ones.
- **Minimal scope:** change only what the task requires; no drive-by refactors or unrelated formatting.
- Do not remove or rewrite existing comments unless fixing accuracy.
- For non-TS JS: **JSDoc** on public helpers where types are not expressed.

When behavior is unclear, prefer a short plan, then implement — still keep edits minimal and testable.
